<p align="center"><font color="#0E024D" face="Arial"><strong>PLAYER SUBMITTED STRATEGY</strong></font></p>
<div align="center"><center>

  <div align="center"><center><table border="0" width="90%">
    <tr>
      <td>
      <center><font face="Arial"><strong><b><font color="#800000">BEGINNING A NECRO</b></font> - <small>Sardonicus, Veeshan</small></strong></font><font face="Arial"></center>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td>
    <small><hr size="1" color="#C0C0C0"><P>
    So, you want to be a Necro, the most hated class in all of Norrath?  Very well, then.  Listen up, and I may be able to help you enough to keep you alive. Remember, never trust an NPC!<P> <P>  First of all, choose which class you want to be.  Human, Erudite, Gnome or Dark Elf.  Each has their own pros and cons.  I will list some of each: <P> <P>  Human: Pro - Good starting locations, even stat distribution.  Con - Lowest base Intelligence.  Even if you put all your bonus points into Int, you will still be far behind any of the other races. <P> Erudite:  Pro - Highest base Intelligence, makes distributing your bonus points easier.  Con - Worst starting location in the game, at the time being.  You cannot leave Erudin until you make level 8 and get your invisibility spell.  You are very KOS in Qeynos.  (I play an Erudite) <P> Gnome: Pro: Highest base Dex (the other prime stat we use), allows you to spend your bonus points on Int.  Infravision is also a plus.  Con - None I can think of other than small race problems, like faction and equipment availability. <P> Dark Elf:  Pro - Ultravision, good starting point, loved in you home city, not KOS in Grobb or Oggok, special abilities (hide).  Con - Hated everywhere else in Norrath.  Double faction hit for being a Dark Elf and being a Necro. <P> <P> You can get more details at the Class Creation Guide on this site. <P> <P>  Ok, the first big step is now done, on to some actual tips and strategy. <P> <P>  For your first four levels, you will be newbie fighting like any other class would be.  However, you have one advantage I don't think any other caster has.  You get a pet at level one!  You have to buy it, though, but it should be the first one you buy.  This is a good habit to get in to, as our pets are the key to our survival.  Pet is always the first spell bought and scribed.  Two other good ones to try and get early is Locate Corpse (players will pay to find their body, you know) and Sense the Dead (makes finding those Decaying Skeletons a lot easier) <P> <P>  Once you reach level 4, you get your first Darkness spell.  This is a very useful line of spells, as it is a Damage over Time (DoT) spell that also slows your target's movement rate.  you can try using this, your pet, and the Fear spell to "reverse kite", but, as I said in my later guide, I found it got resisted a lot.  Keep trying it every level or so, till it works for you.  One spell I recommend you NOT buy is Sense Magic.  I have not had a need for it in my 16 levels of playing a Necro.  There are other spells, later in your life, that will be of no use as well.  If in doubt, ask a higher level Necro for advice. Not too high, mind you, they may have forgotten  =)  <P> <P>  In early levels you will be able to step in and melee a bit while hunting.  This will help raise your Offense and Defense skills, your weapon of choice skill, and also help keep your pet alive.  Don't worry about later levels, as your DoT's will more than compensate for your lack of melee ability.  Right now, your DoT's are a help, but not enough to bring down a monster before it kills your pet.  <P> <P>  Well allrighty then, young Necro, this is all I can give you at the moment, so go out and make yourself famous! <P> <P>-Sardonicus
		
    </small></font></p>
    <p><small><font face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></small></td>
